1
00:00:00,120 --> 00:00:04,760
In this video, we'll unveil the 
secrets of supply and demand trading,  

2
00:00:04,760 --> 00:00:09,364
the only strategy you'll ever 
need to master the markets.

3
00:00:09,364 --> 00:00:11,640
What is Supply and Demand Trading?
 
So, supply and demand trading is  

4
00:00:11,640 --> 00:00:16,840
a strategy that focuses on identifying 
price levels where there's a significant  

5
00:00:16,840 --> 00:00:22,680
imbalance between buyers and sellers.
This imbalance creates what we call supply  

6
00:00:22,680 --> 00:00:26,760
and demand zones on your charts.
 
In the market, there are  

7
00:00:26,760 --> 00:00:31,560
always two competing forces:
Buyers, who represent demand. 

8
00:00:31,560 --> 00:00:37,000
And sellers, who represent supply.
When there are more buyers than sellers at  

9
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:43,680
a certain price level, it creates a demand zone.
When there are more sellers than buyers at a  

10
00:00:43,680 --> 00:00:49,400
price level, it forms a supply zone. 
 
In these zones, you often see large  

11
00:00:49,400 --> 00:00:55,440
unfilled orders from big institutional 
traders like banks and hedge funds. 

12
00:00:55,440 --> 00:01:00,040
Supply and demand trading is powerful 
because it allows you to trade in  

13
00:01:00,040 --> 00:01:05,680
line with what the institutions are doing. 
 
These big players can't hide their massive  

14
00:01:05,680 --> 00:01:12,280
orders, and by identifying supply and demand 
zones, retail traders like us can spot where  

15
00:01:12,280 --> 00:01:16,040
they're likely to be executing their trades.
 
The Dynamics of Supply and Demand in Market Prices 

16
00:01:16,040 --> 00:01:22,080
Let's talk about how supply and demand actually 
influence the prices you see on your charts. 

17
00:01:22,080 --> 00:01:28,240
You see, the price is constantly moving up and 
down, and this movement is a direct result of the  

18
00:01:28,240 --> 00:01:34,120
supply and demand from market participants.
 
When there are more buyers in the market,  

19
00:01:34,120 --> 00:01:40,560
they bring demand and this applies upward 
pressure on prices, pushing them higher. 

20
00:01:40,560 --> 00:01:45,720
When there are more sellers, they bring 
more supply to the market, putting downward  

21
00:01:45,720 --> 00:01:52,520
pressure on prices and pushing them lower.
 
This dynamic between buyers and sellers is  

22
00:01:52,520 --> 00:01:59,960
what we call order flow, and it's the engine that 
actually drives price action and market movement. 

23
00:01:59,960 --> 00:02:04,720
Now, there are two main types of 
orders that make up this order flow:  

24
00:02:04,720 --> 00:02:11,520
passive orders and aggressive orders. 
 
Passive orders are limit orders placed by traders  

25
00:02:11,520 --> 00:02:16,600
who are willing to wait for the price to come 
to their desired level. They're not in a rush. 

26
00:02:17,960 --> 00:02:23,240
Aggressive orders are placed by traders who 
want to execute immediately at the current  

27
00:02:23,240 --> 00:02:29,920
market price. They're not waiting around 
for a specific price; they want in, fast.
  

28
00:02:29,920 --> 00:02:35,040
This constant battle between passive and 
aggressive orders is really what causes  

29
00:02:35,040 --> 00:02:40,840
those explosive price movements you see on your 
charts, when there's a significant imbalance  

30
00:02:40,840 --> 00:02:45,120
between supply and demand.
So, your job is to identify  

31
00:02:45,120 --> 00:02:49,200
where major imbalances are likely to occur.
 
Institutional Traders' Use of Supply and Demand

32
00:02:49,200 --> 00:02:53,920
So, why are institutions so 
interested in supply and demand zones? 

33
00:02:53,920 --> 00:02:57,520
It all comes down to the 
massive size of their orders. 

34
00:02:57,520 --> 00:03:03,600
Institutions like hedge funds and investment 
banks are trading huge positions that can be  

35
00:03:03,600 --> 00:03:09,920
worth millions or even billions of dollars. 
 
And when you're dealing with that kind of volume,  

36
00:03:09,920 --> 00:03:16,440
you CAN’T just enter or exit a trade all 
at once. Imagine trying to buy a billion  

37
00:03:16,440 --> 00:03:20,840
dollars worth of a stock without 
moving the price - it's just not  

38
00:03:20,840 --> 00:03:27,280
possible. There's simply not enough liquidity 
in the market to absorb an order that large.
  

39
00:03:27,280 --> 00:03:33,440
So, instead, institutions have to carefully pick 
their spots and look for areas on the chart where  

40
00:03:33,440 --> 00:03:39,880
they can gradually build or unwind a position 
over time with minimal impact on the price. 

41
00:03:39,880 --> 00:03:44,268
And that's where supply and 
demand zones come into play.

42
00:03:44,268 --> 00:03:44,320
How to Identify Supply and 
Demand Zones on a Chart
  

43
00:03:44,320 --> 00:03:49,040
Now let's break down how to actually 
identify them on your charts. 

44
00:03:49,040 --> 00:03:54,520
The first step is to look for those explosive 
movements where price makes a strong push in  

45
00:03:54,520 --> 00:04:00,760
one direction before quickly reversing. 
 
This could be a sharp rally followed by a  

46
00:04:00,760 --> 00:04:06,480
sudden drop, or a steep decline 
followed by a rapid bounce back. 

47
00:04:06,480 --> 00:04:10,920
These movements often signal that there 
was a significant imbalance between  

48
00:04:10,920 --> 00:04:18,080
buyers and sellers that caused price to spike.
 
Once you've spotted one of these big moves, the  

49
00:04:18,080 --> 00:04:24,840
next step is to mark out the origin of that move.
In other words, the area on your chart where that  

50
00:04:24,840 --> 00:04:30,680
explosive rally or decline actually started.
This is going to be your potential supply  

51
00:04:30,680 --> 00:04:34,200
or demand zone.
 
Now, there are a few  

52
00:04:34,200 --> 00:04:40,760
different types of zones to look out for:
First ones are base zones or range zones:  

53
00:04:40,760 --> 00:04:45,880
These form when price is consolidating 
in a tight range for an extended period  

54
00:04:45,880 --> 00:04:51,600
of time before finally breaking out.
You can think of the edges of that range  

55
00:04:51,600 --> 00:04:57,200
as areas of supply and demand where 
a lot of orders have built up. So,  

56
00:04:57,200 --> 00:05:04,040
when price revisits those levels after a breakout, 
there's a higher probability of a reaction.
  

57
00:05:04,040 --> 00:05:09,360
We can also have pivot zones. These form 
at key turning points in the market,  

58
00:05:09,360 --> 00:05:14,520
like swing highs and lows, or where 
you see price making a sudden change in  

59
00:05:14,520 --> 00:05:20,880
direction. They're often marked by one or two 
candlesticks with distinct characteristics. 
  

60
00:05:20,880 --> 00:05:26,600
For a potential demand zone, you want to look 
for a strong bearish candle where the next  

61
00:05:26,600 --> 00:05:34,160
candle closes back above its high, signaling a 
shift from selling pressure to buying pressure. 

62
00:05:34,160 --> 00:05:37,840
For a supply zone, it's the opposite: 
you're watching for a strong bullish  

63
00:05:37,840 --> 00:05:45,280
candle where the next candle closes below its 
low, indicating a shift from buying to selling. 

64
00:05:45,280 --> 00:05:49,720
The key is that these pivots are 
happening quickly; price isn't spending  

65
00:05:49,720 --> 00:05:57,160
much time in these areas before reversing.
 
To identify fresh zones, you also want to pay  

66
00:05:57,160 --> 00:06:03,000
attention to the overall structure of the price 
action. There are two main types of structures  

67
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:09,200
to look for: continuation and reversal.
 
A continuation structure forms when there's  

68
00:06:09,200 --> 00:06:15,800
an existing trend in place and price is just 
pulling back or correcting against that trend  

69
00:06:15,800 --> 00:06:20,800
before continuing in the same direction.
These are your rally-base-rally  

70
00:06:20,800 --> 00:06:26,800
and drop-base-drop patterns. 
 
If it's an uptrend, you'll see a strong rally,  

71
00:06:26,800 --> 00:06:33,800
a tight range where price forms a small base, 
and then another rally continuing the uptrend. 
  

72
00:06:33,800 --> 00:06:41,920
For a downtrend, you’ll see a sharp drop, a base, 
and then another drop resuming the downtrend.
  

73
00:06:41,920 --> 00:06:46,880
Reversal structures form when price is 
reversing from one trend direction to the  

74
00:06:46,880 --> 00:06:52,640
other. These are your drop-base-rally 
and rally-base-drop patterns. 
  

75
00:06:52,640 --> 00:06:58,680
So, in an uptrend that's starting to lose 
steam, you might see price drop into a base,  

76
00:06:58,680 --> 00:07:04,040
and then launch into a new rally, 
marking the start of a reversal. 
  

77
00:07:04,040 --> 00:07:11,680
And in a downtrend that's starting to turn around, 
you'd see a rally, a base, and then a strong drop,  

78
00:07:11,680 --> 00:07:15,320
signaling the beginning of a new uptrend.
 
Key Principles of Supply and Demand Trading

79
00:07:15,320 --> 00:07:20,880
Now let's talk about the key principles 
that make this strategy so effective. 

80
00:07:20,880 --> 00:07:26,480
The first thing to understand is that supply 
and demand zones are not just random levels on  

81
00:07:26,480 --> 00:07:33,680
your charts; they're areas where the imbalance 
between buyers and sellers is most extreme. 
  

82
00:07:33,680 --> 00:07:39,880
When you see explosive price movements like 
huge rallies or steep drops, that's often a  

83
00:07:39,880 --> 00:07:45,800
sign that there was a serious mismatch between 
the amount of buying and selling pressure.

84
00:07:45,800 --> 00:07:51,360
What's happening in these situations is that 
the aggressive orders from one side are rapidly  

85
00:07:51,360 --> 00:07:57,880
consuming all the available orders from the 
other side, until a new equilibrium is found. 
  

86
00:07:57,880 --> 00:08:03,480
The areas on your charts where these big 
clashes take place are what we call fresh,  

87
00:08:03,480 --> 00:08:08,920
unmitigated supply and demand zones. 
 
One of the key things that separates  

88
00:08:08,920 --> 00:08:13,720
these high probability zones from 
ordinary support and resistance levels,  

89
00:08:13,720 --> 00:08:19,560
is the amount of time price spends in the zone.
You see, when there's a major imbalance between  

90
00:08:19,560 --> 00:08:25,360
buyers and sellers, the price won't 
hang around that area for very long;  

91
00:08:25,360 --> 00:08:29,440
it will quickly spike up or down.
 
So, when you're analyzing your charts,  

92
00:08:30,040 --> 00:08:36,280
one of the things to look for is zones where the 
price only spent a short amount of time before  

93
00:08:36,280 --> 00:08:42,720
making a strong move in either direction.
The less time price spends in that area,  

94
00:08:42,720 --> 00:08:48,240
the more out of balance supply and demand are, 
and the higher the probability of a successful  

95
00:08:48,240 --> 00:08:55,200
trade when the price returns to that zone.
 
Another key principle is to focus on fresh  

96
00:08:55,200 --> 00:09:01,640
unmitigated zones, rather than ones that 
have already been tested multiple times. 

97
00:09:01,640 --> 00:09:07,840
When price revisits a zone, it can absorb some 
of the pending orders that were sitting there,  

98
00:09:07,840 --> 00:09:13,240
making the imbalance less extreme. 
 
 
So, as a general rule, the more times  

99
00:09:13,240 --> 00:09:19,680
a zone has been hit, the weaker it becomes.
This is why it's so important to understand  

100
00:09:19,680 --> 00:09:25,880
the difference between an unmitigated zone and 
one that's already been tested a few times,  

101
00:09:25,880 --> 00:09:31,200
a mitigated one. The trading 
opportunities are very different.
  

102
00:09:31,200 --> 00:09:37,120
Now, of course, there are times when a zone 
can remain valid even after being tested,  

103
00:09:37,120 --> 00:09:43,320
if there's still a significant order imbalance, 
but generally, you want to prioritize fresh  

104
00:09:43,320 --> 00:09:48,360
zones when planning your trades.
 
So, the key things to look for are: 

105
00:09:48,360 --> 00:09:54,080
Zones that form after explosive price movements
Zones where price only spends a short  

106
00:09:54,080 --> 00:09:59,320
amount of time before spiking up or down
And fresh zones that haven't been tested  

107
00:09:59,880 --> 00:10:03,240
or absorbed by the market yet.
 
 
 
Validating Supply and Demand Zones

108
00:10:03,240 --> 00:10:08,680
Now let's talk about how to actually 
validate whether a zone is likely to hold. 

109
00:10:08,680 --> 00:10:13,160
The first thing you want to look 
for is a clear break of structure. 

110
00:10:13,160 --> 00:10:17,880
This means price needs to make a 
decisive move away from the zone  

111
00:10:17,880 --> 00:10:25,240
and take out any nearby swing highs or lows. 
 
If there's no clear break of structure and price  

112
00:10:25,240 --> 00:10:31,760
just hovers around the zone, that's a sign that 
the zone might not be as strong as it seems.
  

113
00:10:31,760 --> 00:10:37,320
Another key concept is the idea of flip 
zones. This is when a previous supply zone  

114
00:10:37,320 --> 00:10:43,400
turns into a demand zone or vice versa.
For example, let's say you have a strong  

115
00:10:43,400 --> 00:10:49,360
supply zone that's been holding price down 
for a while, but then suddenly price rips  

116
00:10:49,360 --> 00:10:54,600
through that level and closes above it.
That's a pretty good indication that the  

117
00:10:54,600 --> 00:11:02,080
zone has flipped from supply to demand and could 
now act as a support level for future pullbacks.
  

118
00:11:02,080 --> 00:11:07,200
But here's the thing: in order for a flip 
zone to be valid, you need to see that  

119
00:11:07,200 --> 00:11:13,240
initial interaction between the two forces.
Don't just assume a zone has flipped because  

120
00:11:13,240 --> 00:11:20,280
price moved past it. Look for that clear battle 
between buyers and sellers and wait for one  

121
00:11:20,280 --> 00:11:26,440
side to decisively overpower the other.
 
Another important factor to consider is  

122
00:11:26,440 --> 00:11:31,720
inducement. We talk about this before. This refers 
to the presence of liquidity in front of the zone  

123
00:11:31,720 --> 00:11:38,400
that could potentially absorb any move against it.
For example, if you're looking at a demand zone,  

124
00:11:38,400 --> 00:11:43,080
you want to see some buy orders 
stacked up in front of that level. 

125
00:11:43,080 --> 00:11:49,040
This could be in the form of a swing low or a 
consolidation pattern - anything that suggests  

126
00:11:49,040 --> 00:11:55,440
there are traders waiting to buy at that price.
 
If there's no liquidity in front of the zone  

127
00:11:55,440 --> 00:12:00,240
and price just slams into it, chances 
are those big players aren't going to  

128
00:12:00,240 --> 00:12:04,960
be too interested in getting involved.
But if there are orders they can trade  

129
00:12:04,960 --> 00:12:09,800
against, they're much more likely 
to step in and defend the level.
  

130
00:12:09,800 --> 00:12:15,920
Of course, even if a zone checks all these 
boxes, it's not guaranteed to hold forever. 

131
00:12:15,920 --> 00:12:20,080
That's why it's also important 
to look at how fresh the zone is. 

132
00:12:20,080 --> 00:12:25,840
In general, zones that have been tested 
multiple times are less likely to produce  

133
00:12:25,840 --> 00:12:31,063
strong reactions than those that 
are being hit for the first time. 
 
  

134
00:12:31,063 --> 00:12:31,120
Supply and Demand Zones vs. 
Support and Resistance Levels

135
00:12:31,120 --> 00:12:36,120
Now let's talk about the difference between 
supply and demand zones and traditional  

136
00:12:36,120 --> 00:12:40,520
support and resistance levels.
While they're similar concepts,  

137
00:12:40,520 --> 00:12:45,760
there are some key distinctions.
 
First off, support and resistance are  

138
00:12:45,760 --> 00:12:52,760
levels where price has previously reversed 
or consolidated multiple times in the past. 

139
00:12:52,760 --> 00:12:59,240
Supply and demand zones, on the other hand, 
are all about fresh, unmitigated levels. 

140
00:12:59,240 --> 00:13:03,960
Rather than focusing on areas that have 
already been touched multiple times,  

141
00:13:03,960 --> 00:13:10,840
these zones represent imbalances between buyers 
and sellers that have just recently formed. 
  

142
00:13:10,840 --> 00:13:16,600
The key difference is that support and resistance 
trading relies on the assumption that past levels  

143
00:13:16,600 --> 00:13:22,520
will continue to hold in the future, whereas 
supply and demand trading looks for new,  

144
00:13:22,520 --> 00:13:28,120
untested zones where the order flow 
is likely to be more significant. 
  

145
00:13:28,120 --> 00:13:34,240
Remember this: support and resistance levels 
are essentially supply and demand zones that  

146
00:13:34,240 --> 00:13:38,520
have already been confirmed.
Once a fresh demand zone gets  

147
00:13:38,520 --> 00:13:43,680
tested and holds, for example, it then 
becomes an established support level. 

148
00:13:43,680 --> 00:13:49,320
The same goes for supply zones, flipping 
to resistance after they've been touched.
  

149
00:13:49,320 --> 00:13:53,760
So, while trading support and 
resistance can certainly be effective,  

150
00:13:53,760 --> 00:13:58,120
especially if a level has proven 
itself multiple times in the past,  

151
00:13:58,120 --> 00:14:03,480
the probability of a reaction tends 
to diminish with each subsequent test. 

152
00:14:03,480 --> 00:14:09,960
This is why you should focus on fresh zones, where 
the initial imbalance between buyers and sellers  

153
00:14:09,960 --> 00:14:13,600
is likely to be the most significant.
 
 
Optimal Entry and Exit Strategies

154
00:14:13,600 --> 00:14:20,960
Now let's talk about some specific entry and exit 
strategies you can use around these key levels. 

155
00:14:20,960 --> 00:14:24,960
One of the simplest and most effective ways 
to enter a trade at a supply or demand zone is  

156
00:14:24,960 --> 00:14:29,240
to simply set a limit order 
directly on the level itself. 

157
00:14:29,240 --> 00:14:36,440
This approach assumes that the zone will hold and 
that price will reverse once it hits your order. 
  

158
00:14:36,440 --> 00:14:41,560
However, there are a couple of potential 
downsides to this aggressive strategy. 

159
00:14:41,560 --> 00:14:47,240
If you set your order too far away from the 
zone, you might miss out on the trade entirely  

160
00:14:47,240 --> 00:14:52,880
if price never quite reaches your price.
Or the second scenario, price might just  

161
00:14:52,880 --> 00:14:57,840
break through your zone with ease.
 
A more conservative approach is to  

162
00:14:57,840 --> 00:15:04,040
wait for a specific candlestick pattern to 
form at the level, before entering a trade. 

163
00:15:04,040 --> 00:15:08,840
For example, you might look for a 
bullish reversal pattern, like a pin  

164
00:15:08,840 --> 00:15:15,560
bar or an engulfing candle, at a demand zone.
The idea behind this strategy is that these  

165
00:15:15,560 --> 00:15:21,840
candlestick formations can give you a bit more 
confirmation that the zone is likely to hold  

166
00:15:21,840 --> 00:15:27,480
and that price is getting ready to reverse. 
 
Another technique you can use to fine-tune your  

167
00:15:27,480 --> 00:15:32,040
entries is to look for specific 
structures on lower time frames. 

168
00:15:32,040 --> 00:15:38,280
For example, let's say you've identified a 
strong demand zone on the 1-hour chart, but  

169
00:15:38,280 --> 00:15:44,400
you want to get more precise with your entry. 
 
Instead of just buying blindly at the level,  

170
00:15:44,400 --> 00:15:50,960
you could drop down to the 15 minute chart and 
look for a reversal pattern, like a double bottom  

171
00:15:50,960 --> 00:15:56,640
or a change of character, to form at the zone.
In this way, you can often get a tighter  

172
00:15:56,640 --> 00:16:01,000
entry with a better risk-to-reward ratio. 
 
 
Assessing the Strength of a Supply or Demand Zone

173
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:06,440
Now let's talk about how to evaluate 
the strength of a supply or demand zone. 

174
00:16:06,440 --> 00:16:13,440
One of the first things to look at is how quickly 
price moves away from the zone after it's formed.  

175
00:16:13,440 --> 00:16:18,920
Generally speaking, the faster price shoots 
away from a level, the stronger that level  

176
00:16:18,920 --> 00:16:26,000
is likely to be. Quick and significant moves 
away from a zone indicate a strong imbalance.
  

177
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:30,640
So, if you see price just rocketing 
away from a zone, that's a pretty good  

178
00:16:30,640 --> 00:16:36,000
sign that there's some serious order flow 
happening there, and that institutions are  

179
00:16:36,000 --> 00:16:41,480
likely defending the level aggressively.
 
Another factor to consider is the amount  

180
00:16:41,480 --> 00:16:46,640
of time price spends at the zone, 
before making that initial move. 

181
00:16:46,640 --> 00:16:51,200
The less time price hangs out at a 
level, the more likely it is to be a  

182
00:16:51,200 --> 00:16:55,320
key turning point in the market.
So, if you see price just kind  

183
00:16:55,320 --> 00:17:00,440
of dip into a demand zone and then 
immediately start rallying higher,  

184
00:17:00,440 --> 00:17:07,920
that's often a signal that big buyers have stepped 
in, and are absorbing all the available supply.
  

185
00:17:07,920 --> 00:17:14,120
The actual size of the move is important 
too. Obviously, if price barely budges  

186
00:17:14,120 --> 00:17:20,400
after hitting a supply or demand level, that's 
not exactly a big endorsement of its strength. 

187
00:17:20,400 --> 00:17:26,240
But if you see an extended move in the opposite 
direction after a zone is tested, that's a sign  

188
00:17:26,240 --> 00:17:32,400
that the level is probably pretty significant.
 
Another thing to watch for is the volume during  

189
00:17:32,400 --> 00:17:39,520
the formation of the zone. Generally speaking, 
you want to see a noticeable uptick in volume,  

190
00:17:39,520 --> 00:17:44,040
as price is testing a key level.
This indicates that there's a lot  

191
00:17:44,040 --> 00:17:49,680
of interest and activity happening at that 
specific price, and that institutions are  

192
00:17:49,680 --> 00:17:55,760
likely absorbing or distributing there.
 
Another factor that can affect the  

193
00:17:55,760 --> 00:18:01,040
strength of a zone is whether or not 
it causes a break of market structure. 

194
00:18:01,040 --> 00:18:07,080
A supply or demand zone that causes a 
break of structure is generally stronger. 

195
00:18:07,080 --> 00:18:11,520
It takes a significant amount of money 
to break market structure, making these  

196
00:18:11,520 --> 00:18:17,600
zones more likely to hold in the future.
 
So, if you see a zone form and then price  

197
00:18:17,600 --> 00:18:23,480
just starts trending in the opposite direction 
and breaking through key levels on the chart,  

198
00:18:23,480 --> 00:18:28,440
that's often a sign that there's some serious 
institutional backing behind the move,  

199
00:18:28,440 --> 00:18:33,745
and that the zone is likely to be 
a key focal point going forward.

200
00:18:33,745 --> 00:18:33,800
Avoiding Common Mistakes in 
Supply and Demand Trading
  

201
00:18:33,800 --> 00:18:39,840
Now let's talk about some of the most frequent 
mistakes that traders make when it comes to supply  

202
00:18:39,840 --> 00:18:45,080
and demand, and how you can avoid them.
One of the biggest errors is trading  

203
00:18:45,080 --> 00:18:48,200
from a weak structure.
This often happens when  

204
00:18:48,200 --> 00:18:53,800
traders zoom in too much on their charts 
and lose sight of the bigger picture. 

205
00:18:53,800 --> 00:18:57,520
They might see a high that failed 
to break the previous one and  

206
00:18:57,520 --> 00:19:03,400
think it's a good supply zone to short. 
 
But if the overall trend is actually bullish,  

207
00:19:03,400 --> 00:19:08,080
they're likely to get smashed trading 
against that dominant direction. 

208
00:19:08,080 --> 00:19:13,720
So, always consider the broader context before 
entering a trade. It's crucial to align your  

209
00:19:13,720 --> 00:19:19,160
trades with the current order flow. 
 
Traders also tend to have the wrong  

210
00:19:19,160 --> 00:19:24,960
expectations of how far price will move 
after hitting a supply or demand zone. 

211
00:19:24,960 --> 00:19:29,040
Old demand zones, for instance, 
often become reaction points  

212
00:19:29,040 --> 00:19:36,280
for pullbacks rather than areas for new highs, 
especially when order flow turns bearish. 
  

213
00:19:36,280 --> 00:19:42,960
So, if you're expecting a full trend reversal from 
an area that's already been tested multiple times,  

214
00:19:42,960 --> 00:19:47,520
you might end up disappointed.
 
It's also a frequent mistake to  

215
00:19:47,520 --> 00:19:52,560
trade from zones with no inducement.
Inducement refers to the liquidity  

216
00:19:52,560 --> 00:19:57,960
that's available in front of a zone.
If there's no structural low or other  

217
00:19:57,960 --> 00:20:03,400
liquidity built up in front of a demand 
zone, that means the only available liquidity  

218
00:20:03,400 --> 00:20:08,200
is actually behind the low itself. 
 
That lack of inducement makes the  

219
00:20:08,200 --> 00:20:11,880
zone more prone to failure.
So, always check where the  

220
00:20:11,880 --> 00:20:17,520
orders are stacked in relation to your zone.
Now, if you want to take an even deeper dive  

221
00:20:17,520 --> 00:20:28,640
into some of the strategies we've touched on 
